3	//! `SYS_EXEC` — replace a target process's program image in place.
4	//!
5	//! PM owns exec (MINIX 3 `pm/exec.c` → `sys_exec`): a user proc `SENDREC`s
6	//! `PM_EXEC` to PM, PM selects a boot-embedded binary and issues `SYS_EXEC`
7	//! naming that proc as the target. The kernel's half is mechanical:
8	//!
9	//! - resolve the binary by name in the MXBI archive
10	//!   ([`BootImage::module_by_name`]);
11	//! - build a brand-new address space and load the ELF into it
12	//!   ([`userland::load_exec_image`] — the same helper that boots the servers);
13	//! - reset the target's register frame to the new entry point with a fresh
14	//!   stack (exec starts clean — no register carries over);
15	//! - swap in the new `(ttbr0_pa, asid)` and tear down the *old* address space
16	//!   (reusing [`do_exit`]'s teardown sequence);
17	//! - unblock the target so the scheduler resumes it at `_start`.
18	//!
19	//! The target is always a clean blocked receiver: in the live flow it is
20	//! mid-`SENDREC` to PM (`RTS_RECEIVING`), so its whole frame is parked. Exec
21	//! discards that continuation — the proc does not return from the `PM_EXEC`
22	//! call; it restarts at the new image's entry. PM therefore sends **no** reply
23	//! on success (this handler resumes the target); on failure the target is left
24	//! untouched on its old image and PM returns the errno to it.
25	//!
26	//! `SELF` and the caller's own endpoint are rejected — tearing down the active
27	//! TTBR0 mid-kernel-call would pull it out from under the running caller (the
28	//! `do_exit` stance). PM is the sole intended holder; it always names a third
29	//! party. exec preserves the proc's pid, privilege, and scheduler — only the
30	//! address space and register frame change.
31	//!
32	//! Target-taking (routed beside `SYS_FORK` in `kernel_call_dispatch`); trust
33	//! model identical to `do_fork` — the `k_call_mask` gate is the only check.
34	//!
35	//! ## Message payload layout (offsets within `Message::payload`)
36	//!
37	//! | offset             | field                            | direction |
38	//! |--------------------|----------------------------------|-----------|
39	//! |  0..4              | target endpoint (i32)            | in        |
40	//! |  4..4+EXEC_NAME_LEN| binary name (NUL-padded)         | in        |
